2026-04-16 12:15:44 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['inverted‑cables indicator LED in control module'] hypothesis_explanation='The control‑module measurements show that the 12 V is present at both the input and the load‑side of the switch, so the switch path to the output node is intact. Yet the output cables and the load‑module input both sit at 0 V, meaning the output node is being hard‑pulled to 0 V somewhere downstream of the switch.\n\nThe test on the indicator branch reports ~12 V from the LED’s cathode to its anode, with both sides of the series resistor at the same potential (~12 V). In a healthy circuit the LED and resistor are in series between the 12 V and 0 V lines; some voltage must appear across the resistor whenever the LED sees nearly the full supply. For both resistor terminals to be at 12 V while the LED sees the full supply, the only consistent explanation is that the LED itself has failed short‑circuit internally, tying the 0 V rail directly to the 12 V rail at the control module input. That short drags the control‑module output and the load‑module input to 0 V under load, explaining why all downstream measurements read 0 V and why the red indicator is (abnormally) on while preventing power from reaching the lamp.\n\nThus the root cause is a shorted inverted‑cables indicator LED inside the control module. Replacing this LED (and any directly associated internal wiring if damaged) should clear the short and restore proper operation of the load and indicators.'
