2026-04-16 12:16:01 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control‑module internal wiring between switch output and output connector (+ line)', 'control‑module output connector (+) contact', 'control‑module internal wiring of 0 V output line or its connector', 'control‑module PCB trace or solder joint from switch output node to output (+) terminal'] hypothesis_explanation='Inside the control module the 12 V input is correct, the switch is closed, and both the switch input and output nodes sit at ~12 V. The inverted‑cables indicator LED sees about 12 V reverse bias (cathode at 12 V, anode at 0 V), exactly as expected when the external polarity is correct. These measurements prove the internal 12 V and 0 V rails of the control module are healthy and that the switch path up to its load‑side node is intact. \n\nHowever, at the external control‑module output and at the load‑module input, both terminals are at 0 V under the same conditions. Therefore the 12 V present at the load‑side of the switch is not being delivered to the output connector. The only way for this to occur, given a good power module and good switching element, is an open circuit (or pair of opens) between the switch output node and the external output terminals of the control module, or a defective connector that fails to carry either the +12 V or the return line to the next module.\n\nThus the remaining fault must lie in the control module’s output path: broken/unsoldered trace or wire from the switch output to the output (+) terminal, or a faulty output connector/contact on either the + or 0 V lead preventing any voltage from appearing at the downstream side. Repairing or re‑making these connections should restore +12 V at the control‑module output and allow the load module lamp to operate when the switch is closed.'
